In [45]:
rows, cols = (2, 1)

week_mean = mean_price.rolling(7).mean()
plt.subplot(rows, cols, 1)
week_mean.plot()
plt.title('Weekly rolling mean price in dollars')
plt.ylabel('Price (USD)')
plt.xlabel('')

weekly_price = (mean_price - week_mean) / week_mean
plt.subplot(rows, cols, 2)
(100 * weekly_price).plot()
plt.title('Percentage of variation around the week mean')
plt.ylabel('Percentage of price variation (%)')

working = list(range(0,4)) + [6]
weekend = [4, 5]
weekly_price['weekday'] = week_days

In [29]:
def plot_wp_hists():
    (100 * weekly_price.price).hist(bins=30, label='all')
    (100 * weekly_price[weekly_price.weekday.isin(working)].price).hist(
        bins=30, label='working day')
    (100 * weekly_price[weekly_price.weekday.isin(weekend)].price).hist(
        bins=30, label='weekend')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('Histogram of the percentual variation of price above the week mean.')
    plt.xlabel('Percentage of variation (%)')
    plt.ylabel('Number of cases')
In [30]:
plot_wp_hists()

Clearly the two modes of the distribution coincide with the working days and weekends. Let's look at that in the time variable.

In [31]:
def plot_wp_trace():
    (100 * weekly_price.price).plot(label='all')
    (100 * weekly_price[weekly_price.weekday.isin(working)].price).plot(label='working day')
    (100 * weekly_price[weekly_price.weekday.isin(weekend)].price).plot(label='weekend')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('Percent of variation above the week mean')
    plt.xlabel('Number of days since the begining of the data')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage of variation (%)')
In [32]:
plot_wp_trace()

What about the mean inter-week deviations from the week mean?

In [38]:
mean_intra_frac = weekly_price.groupby('weekday').price.mean()
dow = ['Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat', 'Sun']
(100 * mean_intra_frac).plot(style='o', markersize=12)
(100 * mean_intra_frac).plot()
plt.xticks(mean_intra_frac.index, dow)
plt.title('Mean intra-week variations')
plt.ylabel('Percentage of variation (%)')
Out[38]:
Text(0,0.5,'Percentage of variation (%)')

The "weekend" days, are in fact the days before a real weekend day, as the reservations include the night.

Resuming, the price spike...¶

In [39]:
frac_spike_rw = (week_mean.max() / week_mean.mean()) - 1.0
frac_spike_week = mean_intra_frac.max()
In [40]:
total_spike = (1.0 + frac_spike_rw) * (1.0 + frac_spike_week) - 1.0
total_spike
Out[40]:
0.09566565972578989
In [46]:
print('If you choose to rent in the days between the begining of June and the' \
      +'begining of September the property will be, in mean, ' \
      '{:.2} % more expensive than the mean price.'.format(100 * frac_spike_rw)
     )
print()
print('If you choose to rent in a weekend, the property will be, in mean, ' \
      +'{:.2}% more expensive.'.format(100 * frac_spike_week))
print()

print('In total, you will probably be paying about {:.2}% '.format(
    100 * total_spike) + 'above the mean, by choosing the expensive days')

If you choose to rent in the days between the begining of June and thebegining of September the property will be, in mean, 6.7 % more expensive than the mean price.

If you choose to rent in a weekend, the property will be, in mean, 2.6% more expensive.

In total, you will probably be paying about 9.6% above the mean, by choosing the expensive days
